👀From The GoFundMe: Joseph Onyango in Uganda is a bold young man, an active yogi, and a yoga teacher with the ambitious vision of raising funds to pay for food, clothes, and yoga equipment to benefit the children in his hometown district of Tororo.

While restrictions related to Covid have been lifted, life is far from being back to normal in Uganda. People were already struggling to meet basic needs before the pandemic, and things have become increasingly challenging since.

Joseph and his family are planning to pay for each child’s regular food and also for uniforms, books, pens, toothbrushes, shoes for walking to school, and associated materials that are in short supply in rural Uganda. This fund is about alleviating a little of the daily struggle, which is part of life in the region. Your gift to this fund contributes towards the possibility for children to grow in a way that might otherwise elude them. Please join me in this effort!

All funds donated here will be wired to Joseph Onyango, and Joseph has committed that all funds he receives will be used only for this project.

Thank you on behalf of Joseph and the children!

👋I’d like to take a moment to quickly introduce myself at this 20,000 Follower Moment! My name is Jonathan Nosan, a Contortionist for over 25 Years, living in Tel Aviv Israel.  Since 13 I loved juggling and magic, and every after school/summer job was performing (birthday parties, Sea World, malls…) but I never thought my passion could be a profession until I saw a circus in Tokyo and also saw my Future. Despite no gymnastic, dance, or natural flexibility I was committed to see what extreme I could push my body as I had pushed my brain (UC Berkeley Grad in Japanese History/ Fulbright Scholar to Kyoto in Design of Sacred Space). So…at 23 I moved to London from Japan to train Theatre and Circus and then a year later to San Francisco for three years of training with Mr. Lu Yi—my Master Trainer. I have Coached Contortion for over 20 years internationally and created the comprehensive online course of CONTORTURE® in 2015 to provide a safe and smart methodology for students who were (and are) self training. I am a strong believer in “Guides” that take us along our Journeys and I have been blessed with 3 main ones: Rene Bazinet from Japan to London, Gypsy Snyder from London to San Francisco, and Mr. Lu Yi who believed in me and trained me to now train others. I am very excited to now be training ”Contorture® Guides”: Certified Teachers to take students to places they know they belong but just need the right push, lift and support. The next Guide Training will be in France May 1-7. So, THANK YOU all for  following me on this trip and I look forward to continued sharing, showing, and growing together.

🥨📚CONTORTION HISTORY 168: THE AMES SISTERS 1937. 🎥 “Play, Girls”
HISTORY by Brian Murphy/Flickr: Left to Right: Marjorie, Barbara, Alice, Mary Eloise & Dorothy.
The Five Ames Sisters
Worked bills with the likes of Milton Berle, Bill” Bo Jangles” Robinson, Rose Marie (eventually of the Dick Van Dyke Show),”Peg Leg” Bates and the Will Maston Trio
(Sammy Davis Jr., his father and uncle).
The girls’ father was originally from Boston and worked for General Electric. The family moved frequently and each of the children was born in a different state. At one point, the family stayed put for nine years in New Orleans and here the dancing began. To give her three older daughters something to do one summer, Doris Ames signed them up for dance lessons at the Josie Corbera School of Dance.There, they studied tap, ballet and acrobatics, and the younger sisters soon followed suit. After their father took a position with Westinghouse, they moved north and went professional,
Their school had so many students they had to use a studio above a theatre. On tour, the sisters, entertained on stage between movies about four times per day. Stops included Buffalo, Montreal and Quebec. Doris was always along and was there to help them with costume changes. She made the costumes, and their father, Frank
Ames, orchestrated all the music. He attended whatever evening shows he could as well as those he could catch while on vacation. The sisters made a movie short at the Universal Studios in Long Island City
Dorothy became a member of the "The Four Merrills" then "The Benard Family Circus". Mary Eloise's agent Billy Creedon, teamed her with Dottie Pananski and Frankie Adagio to form "The Three Wells" who were written up in Variety and did theatres in the States as well as USO tours.
After Adagio went into the service, another male joined them and they worked with Sammy Kaye, and Frank Sinatra, drummer Gene Krupa as well as Jimmy Durante, and performed at the Apollo Theatre in New York. Mary Eloise later joined "The Three Rays".
Barbara passed away in 2000, Marjorie in 2002. Dorothy (97 year old) Alice passed away October, 2011, Mary Eloise passed September 12, 2013
